-- China stocks rebound, led by banking and property shares
-- By the Chen Yixin
-- Wed Dec 10, 2014 02:09AM EST
-- None



SHANGHAI, Dec 10 (Reuters) - China stocks rebound on Wednesday from the previous day's tumble, led by banking, property and small-cap shares as investors remained bullish about the market.

The CSI300 index <.CSI300> of the largest listed companies in Shanghai and Shenzhen rose 3.7 percent, to 3,221.55, while the Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> gained 2.9 percent, to 2,940.01 points. The China CSI300 banking index <.CSI300BI> rose about 4 percent, reversing the morning session's fall, after diving 9 percent on Tuesday. The CSI300 property index <.CSICMRE> jumped 4.5 percent. The Nasdaq-style ChiNext Composite Index <.CHINEXTC> of mostly high-tech start-ups listed in Shenzhen ended up 3.8 percent. Among the most active stocks in Shanghai were Bank of China <601988.SS>, up 1.8 percent to 3.39 yuan; China Shipbuilding <601989.SS>, up 10.0 percent to 8.46 yuan and CITIC Securities Co <600030.SS>, up 2.9 percent to 27.30 yuan. In Shenzhen, BOE Technology <000725.SZ>, up 3.3 percent to 3.14 yuan; Changjiang Securities Co <000783.SZ>, up 5.0 percent to 14.92 yuan and TCL CORP <000100.SZ>, up 7.0 percent to 3.84 yuan were among the most actively traded. Foreign investment flowing into Shanghai from Hong Kong through the mutual market access pilot programme took up 1.94 billion yuan <.NQUOTA.SH> of the 13 billion yuan daily quota.